{"title_page": "Mrs. Wiggins", "text_new": "\"'''Mrs. Wiggins'''\" (also known as '''\"Mr. Tudball and Mrs. Wiggins\"''') is a series of [[sketch comedy|comedy sketches]] featured on ''[[The Carol Burnett Show]]'', with one installment airing on ''[[Carol Burnett & Company]]''. ''The Carol Burnett Show'' introduced the skit series during its ninth season in 1975\u201376 and continued to air new installments for the remainder of its 11-season run, through its final season in 1977\u201378. However, the final installment of \"Mrs. Wiggins\" would not air until August 18, 1979 on a different four-week summer series titled ''Carol Burnett & Company''. This was the only installment of \"Mrs. Wiggins\" that did not air on ''The Carol Burnett Show''. ''The Carol Burnett Show'' had completed its run almost a year and a half earlier on March 29, 1978. All together, there were 19 installments of \"Mrs. Wiggins\" sketches.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timelife.com/products/the-carol-burnett-show-the-ultimate-collection |title=THE CAROL BURNETT SHOW: THE ULTIMATE COLLECTION |publisher=Time Life |date= |accessdate=2016-06-26}}</ref>\n\n==Premise==\n\"Mrs. Wiggins\" features two characters created by [[Tim Conway]]: Mr. Bernie Tudball (played by Conway) and Mrs. Wanda Wiggins (played by [[Carol Burnett]]). [[Vicki Lawrence]] would occasionally play Mr. Tudball's wife. Mr. Tudball is a businessman with an off-color [[toupee]] and a mock [[Romanian language|Romanian]] accent, pronouncing his secretary's name \"Mrs. Uh-Whiggins\".<ref>King, Susan. \"[http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/showtracker/la-et-st-tim-conway-20131112-story.html Tim Conway's life off script]\", ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', November 11, 2013. Accessed September 21, 2016.</ref> Mrs. Wiggins is his [[secretary]], a \"bimbo who the IQ fairy never visited\".<ref name=\"Carol Burnett and Tim Conway: bonded through comedy\">{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2010/apr/25/entertainment/la-et-burnett-conway-20100426 |title=Carol Burnett and Tim Conway: bonded through comedy |publisher=Los Angeles Times |date=April 25, 2010 |accessdate=2016-06-26}}</ref> She was notably recognized by how she walked in her skirt, as designed by [[Bob Mackie]], and her near-constant fingernail filing. The sketches center on Mr. Tudbull's frustration over Mrs. Wiggins' dimwittedness, such as not being able to properly use the office intercom system.{{citation needed|date = February 2017}}\n\n==Background==\nTim Conway created the sketch after ''The Carol Burnett Show'' writers' office secretary, Charlene, would constantly press the wrong button on the intercom.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.emmytvlegends.org/interviews/people/tim-conway#| title=Interview: Tim Conway| publisher=Archive of American Television| date=29 April 2004| last=Herman| first=Karen}}</ref>\n\nMrs. Wiggins was originally written to be a little old lady, but Bob Mackie decided to go another route.<ref name=\"Carol Burnett and Tim Conway: bonded through comedy\">{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2010/apr/25/entertainment/la-et-burnett-conway-20100426 |title=Carol Burnett and Tim Conway: bonded through comedy |publisher=Los Angeles Times |date=April 25, 2010 |accessdate=2016-06-26}}</ref> He decided to base the look of Mrs. Wiggins on the kind of secretary that would sit around and file her nails and go to lunch.<ref>{{Cite web | first= | last= | title=Bob Mackie |work=Archive of American Television | date=June 29, 2000  | url=http://www.emmytvlegends.org/interviews/people/bob-mackie# | accessdate=Jun 26, 2016}}</ref> In the costuming of Mrs. Wiggins, Mackie put Burnett in a very tight skirt that would control the way she walked. He told Burnett to stick her behind in the bagging part in the back of the skirt, and this gave her the \"Wiggins walk.\"<ref>{{Cite web | first= | last= | title=Carol Burnett |work=Archive of American Television | date=April 29, 2003  | url=http://www.emmytvlegends.org/interviews/people/carol-burnett | accessdate=June 26, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Sketches==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:left\"\n|-\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" | Season\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" | Episode\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" | Airdate\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" | Title & Description\n|-\n| Season 9\n| Ep 17\n| January 10, 1976\n| ''The Intercom'' \u2013 Mr. Tudball has difficulty teaching Mrs. Wiggins how to use the office's new intercom system.\n|-\n| Season 9\n| Ep 21\n| February 14, 1976\n| ''The Intercom\u2026Again'' \u2013 Mr. Tudball has even more difficulty teaching Mrs. Wiggins the workings of the office intercom.\n|-\n| Season 9\n| Ep 24\n| March 13, 1976\n| ''The Birthday Party'' \u2013 Mr. Tudball attempts to surprise Mrs. Wiggins on her birthday.\n|-\n| Season 10\n| Ep 4\n| October 16, 1976\n| ''The Vending Machine'' \u2013 Mr. Tudball does battle with a difficult [[coffee vending machine]].\n|-\n| Season 10\n| Ep 7\n| October 30, 1976\n| ''Buzz Off'' \u2013 Mr. Tudball gets into trouble with a newly-installed door buzzer system, and Mrs. Wiggins is no help.\n|-\n| Season 10\n| Ep 10\n| November 27, 1976\n| Mr. Tudball tries to get Mrs. Wiggins to cover for him by lying to his wife.\n|-\n| Season 10\n| Ep 13\n| December 25, 1976\n| ''Mrs. Wiggins at Lunch'' \u2013 Mr. Tudball treats Mrs. Wiggins to a lunch in honor of National Secretary Week. \n|-\n| Season 10\n| Ep 17\n| January 29, 1977\n| ''Mrs. Wiggins' Date'' \u2013 Mrs. Wiggins has a millionaire date ([[Rock Hudson]]) for lunch, but she wants to dump him.\n|-\n| Season 10\n| Ep 18\n| February 5, 1977\n| ''Enter Mrs. Tudball'' \u2013 Mr. Tudball is thrown out of the house by his wife for playing poker.\n|-\n| Season 10\n| Ep 19\n| February 12, 1977\n| ''The Vacation'' \u2013 Mr. Tudball teaches Mrs. Wiggins to play blackjack in preparation for her Las Vegas vacation.\n|-\n| Season 10\n| Ep 23\n| March 26, 1977\n| ''The Fire Drill'' \u2013 Mr. Tudball has a hard time coordinating a fire-safety plan with Mrs. Wiggins before an inspector arrives.\n|-\n| Season 11\n| Ep 4\n| October 15, 1977\n| Mr. Tudball pick a fitting coffin for Mrs. Wiggins' deceased canary.\n|-\n| Season 11\n| Ep 6\n| October 29, 1977\n| ''Ol' Paint'' \u2013 It's painting day at the office and Mr. Tudball relies on Mrs. Wiggins for help.\n|-\n| Season 11\n| Ep 9\n| November 19, 1977\n| ''Mrs. Wiggins in Hawaii'' \u2013\n|-\n| Season 11\n| Ep 11\n| December 3, 1977\n| Mr. Tudball nudges Mrs. Wiggins to clean up her desk which leads to office chaos.\n|-\n| Season 11\n| Ep 13\n| December 18, 1977\n| ''Christmas Eve'' \u2013 Mr. Tudball and Mrs. Wiggins enjoy a champagne-laden Christmas Eve.\n|-\n| Season 11\n| Ep 20\n| February 26, 1978\n| ''Car Problem'' \u2013 Mr. Tudball takes a telephone call from Mrs. Wiggins' car repairman, thinking it's her doctor.\n|-\n| Season 11\n| Ep 24\n| March 29, 1978\n| ''Flashbacks'' \u2013 Mr. Tudball is moving his office and has a flashback to the first time he interviewed Mrs. Wiggins\n|-\n| ''[[Carol Burnett & Company]]''\n| Ep 1.1\n| August 18, 1979\n| ''Mrs. Wiggins and the Energy Crisis'' \u2013 Mr. Tudball and Mrs. Wiggins make a mess of energy conservation.\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{The Carol Burnett Show}}\n\n[[Category:Comedy sketches]]\n[[Category:Fictional secretaries|Wiggins]]\n[[Category:Carol Burnett]]\n", "text_old": "\"'''Mrs. Wiggins'''\" (also known as '''\"Mr. Tudball and Mrs. Wiggins\"''') is a series of [[sketch comedy|comedy sketches]] featured on ''[[The Carol Burnett Show]]'', with one installment airing on ''[[Carol Burnett & Company]]''. ''The Carol Burnett Show'' introduced the skit series during its ninth season in 1975\u201376 and continued to air new installments for the remainder of its 11-season run, through its final season in 1977\u201378. However, the final installment of \"Mrs. Wiggins\" wouldn't air until August 18, 1979 on a different four-week summer series titled ''Carol Burnett & Company''. This was the only installment of \"Mrs. Wiggins\" that did not air on ''The Carol Burnett Show''. ''The Carol Burnett Show'' had completed its run almost a year and a half earlier on March 29, 1978. All together, there were 19 installments of \"Mrs. Wiggins\" sketches.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timelife.com/products/the-carol-burnett-show-the-ultimate-collection |title=THE CAROL BURNETT SHOW: THE ULTIMATE COLLECTION |publisher=Time Life |date= |accessdate=2016-06-26}}</ref>\n\n==Premise==\n\"Mrs. Wiggins\" features two characters created by [[Tim Conway]]: Mr. Bernie Tudball (played by Conway) and Mrs. Wanda Wiggins (played by [[Carol Burnett]]). [[Vicki Lawrence]] would occasionally play Mr. Tudball's wife. Mr. Tudball is a businessman with an off-color [[toupee]] and a mock [[Romanian language|Romanian]] accent, pronouncing his secretary's name \"Mrs. Uh-Whiggins\".<ref>King, Susan. \"[http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/showtracker/la-et-st-tim-conway-20131112-story.html Tim Conway's life off script]\", ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', November 11, 2013. Accessed September 21, 2016.</ref> Mrs. Wiggins is his [[secretary]], a \"bimbo who the IQ fairy never visited\".<ref name=\"Carol Burnett and Tim Conway: bonded through comedy\">{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2010/apr/25/entertainment/la-et-burnett-conway-20100426 |title=Carol Burnett and Tim Conway: bonded through comedy |publisher=Los Angeles Times |date=April 25, 2010 |accessdate=2016-06-26}}</ref> She was notably recognized by how she walked in her skirt, as designed by [[Bob Mackie]], and her near-constant fingernail filing. The sketches center on Mr. Tudbull's frustration over Mrs. Wiggins' dimwittedness, such as not being able to properly use the office intercom system.{{citation needed|date = February 2017}}\n\n==Background==\nTim Conway created the sketch after ''The Carol Burnett Show'' writers' office secretary, Charlene, would constantly press the wrong button on the intercom.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.emmytvlegends.org/interviews/people/tim-conway#| title=Interview: Tim Conway| publisher=Archive of American Television| date=29 April 2004| last=Herman| first=Karen}}</ref>\n\nMrs. Wiggins was originally written to be a little old lady, but Bob Mackie decided to go another route.<ref name=\"Carol Burnett and Tim Conway: bonded through comedy\">{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2010/apr/25/entertainment/la-et-burnett-conway-20100426 |title=Carol Burnett and Tim Conway: bonded through comedy |publisher=Los Angeles Times |date=April 25, 2010 |accessdate=2016-06-26}}</ref> He decided to base the look of Mrs. Wiggins on the kind of secretary that would sit around and file her nails and go to lunch.<ref>{{Cite web | first= | last= | title=Bob Mackie |work=Archive of American Television | date=June 29, 2000  | url=http://www.emmytvlegends.org/interviews/people/bob-mackie# | accessdate=Jun 26, 2016}}</ref> In the costuming of Mrs. Wiggins, Mackie put Burnett in a very tight skirt that would control the way she walked. He told Burnett to stick her behind in the bagging part in the back of the skirt, and this gave her the \"Wiggins walk.\"<ref>{{Cite web | first= | last= | title=Carol Burnett |work=Archive of American Television | date=April 29, 2003  | url=http://www.emmytvlegends.org/interviews/people/carol-burnett | accessdate=June 26, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Sketches==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:left\"\n|-\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" | Season\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" | Episode\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" | Airdate\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" | Title & Description\n|-\n| Season 9\n| Ep 17\n| January 10, 1976\n| ''The Intercom'' \u2013 Mr. Tudball has difficulty teaching Mrs. Wiggins how to use the office's new intercom system.\n|-\n| Season 9\n| Ep 21\n| February 14, 1976\n| ''The Intercom\u2026Again'' \u2013 Mr. Tudball has even more difficulty teaching Mrs. Wiggins the workings of the office intercom.\n|-\n| Season 9\n| Ep 24\n| March 13, 1976\n| ''The Birthday Party'' \u2013 Mr. Tudball attempts to surprise Mrs. Wiggins on her birthday.\n|-\n| Season 10\n| Ep 4\n| October 16, 1976\n| ''The Vending Machine'' \u2013 Mr. Tudball does battle with a difficult [[coffee vending machine]].\n|-\n| Season 10\n| Ep 7\n| October 30, 1976\n| ''Buzz Off'' \u2013 Mr. Tudball gets into trouble with a newly-installed door buzzer system, and Mrs. Wiggins is no help.\n|-\n| Season 10\n| Ep 10\n| November 27, 1976\n| Mr. Tudball tries to get Mrs. Wiggins to cover for him by lying to his wife.\n|-\n| Season 10\n| Ep 13\n| December 25, 1976\n| ''Mrs. Wiggins at Lunch'' \u2013 Mr. Tudball treats Mrs. Wiggins to a lunch in honor of National Secretary Week. \n|-\n| Season 10\n| Ep 17\n| January 29, 1977\n| ''Mrs. Wiggins' Date'' \u2013 Mrs. Wiggins has a millionaire date ([[Rock Hudson]]) for lunch, but she wants to dump him.\n|-\n| Season 10\n| Ep 18\n| February 5, 1977\n| ''Enter Mrs. Tudball'' \u2013 Mr. Tudball is thrown out of the house by his wife for playing poker.\n|-\n| Season 10\n| Ep 19\n| February 12, 1977\n| ''The Vacation'' \u2013 Mr. Tudball teaches Mrs. Wiggins to play blackjack in preparation for her Las Vegas vacation.\n|-\n| Season 10\n| Ep 23\n| March 26, 1977\n| ''The Fire Drill'' \u2013 Mr. Tudball has a hard time coordinating a fire-safety plan with Mrs. Wiggins before an inspector arrives.\n|-\n| Season 11\n| Ep 4\n| October 15, 1977\n| Mr. Tudball pick a fitting coffin for Mrs. Wiggins' deceased canary.\n|-\n| Season 11\n| Ep 6\n| October 29, 1977\n| ''Ol' Paint'' \u2013 It's painting day at the office and Mr. Tudball relies on Mrs. Wiggins for help.\n|-\n| Season 11\n| Ep 9\n| November 19, 1977\n| ''Mrs. Wiggins in Hawaii'' \u2013\n|-\n| Season 11\n| Ep 11\n| December 3, 1977\n| Mr. Tudball nudges Mrs. Wiggins to clean up her desk which leads to office chaos.\n|-\n| Season 11\n| Ep 13\n| December 18, 1977\n| ''Christmas Eve'' \u2013 Mr. Tudball and Mrs. Wiggins enjoy a champagne-laden Christmas Eve.\n|-\n| Season 11\n| Ep 20\n| February 26, 1978\n| ''Car Problem'' \u2013 Mr. Tudball takes a telephone call from Mrs. Wiggins' car repairman, thinking it's her doctor.\n|-\n| Season 11\n| Ep 24\n| March 29, 1978\n| ''Flashbacks'' \u2013 Mr. Tudball is moving his office and has a flashback to the first time he interviewed Mrs. Wiggins\n|-\n| ''[[Carol Burnett & Company]]''\n| Ep 1.1\n| August 18, 1979\n| ''Mrs. Wiggins and the Energy Crisis'' \u2013 Mr. Tudball and Mrs. Wiggins make a mess of energy conservation.\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{The Carol Burnett Show}}\n\n[[Category:Comedy sketches]]\n[[Category:Fictional secretaries|Wiggins]]\n[[Category:Carol Burnett]]\n", "name_user": "Moe1810", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mrs._Wiggins"}
{"title_page": "Death Bed", "text_new": "{{short description|2019 single by Powfu featuring Beabadoobee}}\n{{Other uses|Deathbed (disambiguation){{!}}Deathbed}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Death Bed\n| type       = single\n| cover      = Powfu - Death Bed.png\n| alt        =\n| artist     = [[Powfu]] featuring [[Beabadoobee]]\n| album      =\n| format     =\n* [[Music download|Digital download]]\n* [[Streaming media|streaming]]\n| recorded   = 2019\n| released   = <!-- Commercial release date, not SoundCloud upload date -->{{start date|2020|02|08|mf=y}}\n| genre      = [[Lo-fi hip hop]]<!-- Sourced in prose -->\n| length     = {{duration|m=2|s=53}}\n| label      = [[Columbia Records|Columbia]]\n| writer     =\n* [[Powfu|Isaiah Faber]]\n* [[Beabadoobee|Beatrice Laus]]\n* Oscar Lang\n| producer   = Otterpop\n| chronology = [[Beabadoobee]]\n| prev_title = I Wish I Was Stephen Malkmus\n| prev_year  = 2019\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{YouTube|jJPMnTXl63E|\"Death Bed\"}}}}\n}}\n\"'''Death Bed'''\", later re-titled as \"'''Death Bed (Coffee for Your Head)'''\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://open.spotify.com/track/7eJMfftS33KTjuF7lTsMCx|title=\"death bed (coffee for your head) (feat. beabadoobee)\" on Spotify}}</ref> (stylized in [[Letter case#All lowercase|all lowercase]]) is a song by Canadian rapper [[Powfu]], featuring Filipino-British singer-songwriter [[Beabadoobee]]. The song was initially uploaded to [[SoundCloud]] in 2019; following Powfu signing to [[Columbia Records]], the song was released on streaming services on February 8, 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://genius.com/a/powfu-breaks-down-the-meaning-of-death-bed|title=Powfu Breaks Down The Meaning Of \"Death Bed\"|website=[[Genius (website)|Genius]]|last=Reneau|first=Steven|date=March 6, 2020|accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref> The song samples the 2017 song \"Coffee\" by Beabadoobee, who is credited as a feature.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://headlineplanet.com/home/2020/03/08/powfu-beabadoobees-death-bed-picks-up-pop-radio-airplay-reaches-50-million-spotify-streams/|title=Powfu & Beabadoobee's \"Death Bed\" Picks Up Pop Radio Airplay, Reaches 50 Million Spotify Streams|website=Headline Planet|last=Cantor|first=Brian|date=March 8, 2020|accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe song went viral on the video sharing app [[TikTok]] in early 2020.<ref name=\"Genius BG\">{{cite web|url=https://genius.com/a/powfu-s-death-bed-samples-beabadoobee-s-coffee|title=Powfu's Viral Hit \"Death Bed\" Arrives On Streaming Services After Lengthy Sample Clearance Delay|website=Genius|last=Fu|first=Eddie|date=February 13, 2020|accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nThe song's commercial release was delayed by a year due to the clearance of the [[Sampling (music)|sample]] of Beabadoobee's 2017 song \"Coffee\". Powfu said on [[Twitter]] in April 2019 that he had not put it on [[Spotify]] because he was \"scared [he'd] get in trouble from the sample [he] use[s] in it\", but said he \"would upload it anyway\" and told his followers to give him \"a week and a half\". It was finally released to streaming and download services in February 2020.<ref name=\"Genius BG\"/>\n\n==Composition==\nColumbia's British subsidiary [[Sony Music UK]] described it as a \"lo-fi hip hop single\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pressparty.com/pg/newsdesk/sonymusicuk/view/205330/|title=Powfu \u2013 New Single 'Death Bed' Feat Beabadoobee Out Now|publisher=[[Sony Music UK]]|via=[[Pressparty]]|date=March 2, 2020|accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2020)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Australia ([[ARIA Charts|ARIA]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ariacharts.com.au/charts/singles-chart|title=ARIA Australian Top 50 Singles|publisher=[[Australian Recording Industry Association]]|date=April 13, 2020|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n| 5\n|-\n{{single chart|Austria|11|artist=Powfu feat. Beabadoobee|song=Death Bed|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 22, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Flanders|7|artist=Powfu feat. Beabadoobee|song=Death Bed|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 24, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Wallonia|46|artist=Powfu feat. Beabadoobee|song=Death Bed|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 4, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Canada|16|artist=Beabadoobee|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 21, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Czechdigital|10|year=2020|week=16|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 21, 2020}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Denmark ([[Tracklisten]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hitlisten.nu/default.asp?w=13&y=2020&list=t40|title=Track Top-40 Uge 13, 2020|publisher=[[Hitlisten]]|accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n| 10\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Estonia ([[Eesti Tipp-40]])<ref name=\"estonianchart\">{{Cite web|url=https://ekspress.delfi.ee/areen/eesti-tipp-40-muusikas-selle-nadala-kangelased-on-the-weeknd-ja-ag?id=89401195|title=Eesti Tipp-40 Muusikas: Selle n\u00e4dala kangelased on The Weeknd ja AG|language=Estonian|last=Nestor|first=Siim|website=[[Eesti Ekspress]]|date=March 31, 2020|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n| 9\n|-\n{{single chart|Finland|9|artist=Powfu feat. Beabadoobee|song=Death Bed|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 23, 2020}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| France ([[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique|SNEP]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://snepmusique.com/les-tops/le-top-de-la-semaine/top-albums/?semaine=16?&annee=2020&categorie=Top%20Singles|title=Top Singles (Week 16, 2020)|publisher=[[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique]]|language=French|accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref>\n| 25\n|-\n{{single chart|Germany2|18|songid=1954287|artist=Powfu feat. Beabadoobee|song=Death Bed|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 17, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Hungarystream|13|year=2020|week=16|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 23, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Ireland4|7|date=20200417|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 18, 2020}}\n|