azil.\n{{Div col}}\n*[[Amanay\u00e9]] ([[Ararandeura]]), Brazil\n*[[Arawet\u00e9 people|Arawet\u00e9]] ([[Arauet\u00e9]], [[B\u00efde]]), Par\u00e1, Brazil\n*[[Aw\u00e1 (Guaj\u00e1)]], Brazil\n*[[Ch'unchu people|Ch'unchu]], Peru\n*[[Ge (people)|Ge]]\n*[[Guajaj\u00e1ra]] ([[Guajajara]]), Maranh\u00e3o, Brazil\n*[[Guarani people|Guarani]], Paraguay\n*[[Ka'apor]], Maranh\u00e3o, Brazil\n*[[Kuruaya]], Par\u00e1, Brazil\n*[[Marajoara]], Precolumbian culture, Par\u00e1, Brazil\n*[[Panar\u00e1]], Mato Grosso and Par\u00e1, Brazil\n*[[Parakan\u00e3]] ([[Paracana]])\n*[[Suru\u00ed do Par\u00e1 people|Suru\u00ed do Par\u00e1]], Par\u00e1, Brazil\n*[[Temb\u00e9]] ([[Tembe]])\n*[[Turiw\u00e1ra]] ([[Turiwara]])\n*[[Wayampi]]\n*[[Zo'\u00e9 people]], Par\u00e1, Brazil\n{{Div col end}}\n\n=== Southern Amazon ===\nThis region includes southern Brazil ([[Mato Grosso]], [[Mato Grosso do Sul]], parts of [[Par\u00e1]], and [[Rond\u00f4nia]]) and Eastern Bolivia ([[Beni Department]]).\n{{Div col}}\n*[[Apiac\u00e1 people|Apiac\u00e1]] ([[Apiak\u00e1]]), Mato Grosso and Par\u00e1, Brazil<ref>[http://pib.socioambiental.org/en/povo/apiaka \"Apiak\u00e1: Introduction\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120330091927/http://pib.socioambiental.org/en/povo/apiaka |date=2012-03-30 }}. Instituto Socioambiental: Povos Ind\u00edgenas no Brasil. Retrieved 28 March 2012</ref>\n*[[Assurin\u00ed do Toncantins]] ([[Tocantin]])\n*[[Aweti]] ([[Aueto]]), Mato Grosso, Brazil\n*[[Bakair\u00ed]] ([[Bakairi]])\n*[[Ch\u00e1cobo]] ([[Chacobo]]), northwest Beni Department, Bolivia<ref name=bolivia/>\n*[[Chiquitano people|Chiquitano]] ([[Chiquitos|Chiquito]], [[Tarapecosi]]), Brazil and Santa Cruz, Bolivia<ref name=bolivia/>\n*[[Cinta Larga]], Mato Grosso, Brazil\n*[[Enawene Nawe people|Enawene Nawe]], Mato Grosso, Brazil\n*[[Gavi\u00e3o of Rond\u00f4nia]]\n*[[Guarayu]] ([[Guarayo people|Guarayo]]), Bolivia<ref name=bolivia/>\n*[[Ikpeng]] ([[Xicao]]), Mato Grosso, Brazil\n*[[Itene people|Itene]], Beni 